    "cityIching": "I Ching",
    "longDescShanghai": "<p>Shanghai, a global financial hub, is a city of superlatives. Its futuristic skyline, dominated by the Shanghai Tower and the Oriental Pearl TV Tower, is a sight to behold.</p><p>Stroll along the Bund to admire the colonial-era architecture, explore the trendy boutiques and art galleries in the French Concession, or find tranquility in the classical Yu Garden. Shanghai is a testament to China's rapid development and a must-visit for any traveler.</p>",
    "longDescSuzhou": "<p>Suzhou, a UNESCO World Heritage city in Jiangsu province, is famous for its classical gardens, silk production, and network of canals. Often called the <strong>Venice of the East</strong>, it offers a serene contrast to China's modern megacities.</p><p>Explore the Humble Administrator's Garden, walk along the historic Pingjiang Road canal, and visit the Suzhou Silk Museum. Suzhou's classical gardens — including the Humble Administrator's Garden and Lingering Garden — are among the most celebrated in China.</p><p>Don't miss the Tiger Hill pagoda, the ancient Lingering Garden, and the vibrant Pingjiang Road historical district.</p>",
    "longDescXian": "<p>Xi'an is one of the oldest cities in China and the eastern terminus of the Silk Road. Its most famous attraction is the Terracotta Army, a vast collection of life-sized terracotta sculptures depicting the armies of Qin Shi Huang, the first Emperor of China.</p><p>The city itself is surrounded by a well-preserved ancient city wall, which you can cycle on for incredible views. Don't miss the Muslim Quarter for a vibrant culinary experience.</p>",
    "longDescGuilin": "<p>Guilin's landscape is the stuff of classic Chinese paintings. Located in Southern China, it is world-renowned for its otherworldly karst topography.</p><p>The best way to experience its beauty is by taking a cruise down the Li River, where you'll see limestone peaks, bamboo groves, and tranquil villages. You can also explore the Reed Flute Cave, a natural limestone cave with impressive stalactites and stalagmites illuminated by colorful lights.</p>",
    "longDescHuangshan": "<p>Huangshan (黄山), literally 'Yellow Mountain,' is one of China's most celebrated scenic destinations and a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1990. Known as the 'No. 1 Mountain of China,' it towers at 1,864 meters above sea level in Anhui Province.</p><p>The mountain is world-famous for its <strong>sea of clouds</strong> (云海), <strong>oddly-shaped pines</strong> (奇松), <strong>granite peaks</strong> (怪石), and hot springs. The interplay of these four wonders creates an ethereal landscape that has inspired Chinese painters and poets for centuries.</p><p>Key attractions include <strong>Beihai (North Sea)</strong>, <strong>光明顶 (Bright Summit)</strong>, <strong>迎客松 (Guest-Greeting Pine)</strong>, and the spectacular <strong>丹霞峰 (Danxia Peak)</strong>. The best time to visit is from April to November, with autumn offering the most dramatic colors.</p>",
    "longDescZhangjiajie": "<p>Zhangjiajie is famous for its towering pillar-like sandstone formations set within a UNESCO-listed national park – an otherworldly landscape perfect for hiking and photography.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li><strong>Zhangjiajie National Forest Park</strong> – home to the famous quartz-sandstone pillars.</li><li><strong>Avatar Hallelujah Mountains</strong> – scenic viewpoints inspired cinematic landscapes.</li><li><strong>Glass Bridge (Zhangjiajie Grand Canyon)</strong> – a thrilling suspended walkway with dramatic views.</li></ul>",
    "cityChengdu": "Chengdu",
    "descChengdu": "Home to giant pandas and the gateway to Sichuan's ancient heritage.",
    "longDescChengdu": "<p>Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan province, is a city where ancient traditions blend seamlessly with modern life. It is world-famous for its Giant Panda Base and Research Center, where visitors can observe these beloved creatures in semi-natural habitats.</p><p>The city is also the gateway to some of China's most stunning natural landscapes, including the Buddha statue at Leshan and the scenic mountains of Jiuzhaigou. In the city itself, explore the historic Jinli Street, relax in People's Park, and experience the laid-back Sichuan lifestyle. Chengdu is also internationally recognized as the UNESCO City of Gastronomy -- its spicy Sichuan cuisine is legendary.</p><h3 id=\"panda-base\" class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">Chengdu Panda Base</h3><p>The <strong>Chengdu Research Base of Giant Panda Breeding</strong> (成都大熊猫繁育研究基地) is the top attraction in Chengdu. Located just 10 km from the city center, it houses over 50 giant pandas and is one of the most successful panda breeding programs in the world.</p><p><strong>Opening hours:</strong> 07:30-18:00. <strong>Ticket:</strong> ~55 yuan. <strong>Metro:</strong> Line 3 to Panda Base Station.</p><h3 id=\"jinli-street\" class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">Jinli Street</h3><p><strong>Jinli Street</strong> (锦里) is a famous pedestrian street known for its traditional architecture, local snacks, tea houses, and crafts. One of the oldest commercial streets in China, it comes alive in the evening with lanterns and street performances.</p><h3 id=\"dujiangyan\" class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">Dujiangyan Irrigation System</h3><p>About 50 km from Chengdu, the <strong>Dujiangyan Irrigation System</strong> (都江堰) is a UNESCO World Heritage site -- an ancient water management project still in use today. An impressive feat of ancient engineering and a scenic area for hiking.</p><h3 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">How to get there</h3><p><strong>By air:</strong> Chengdu Tianfu International Airport (TFU) has domestic and international flights. Metro, bus, or taxi to city center (45 min).</p><p><strong>By train:</strong> High-speed trains from Beijing (~7h), Shanghai (~10h), Xi'an (~3h). Chengdu East Railway Station is closest to tourist areas.</p><h3 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">Best time to visit</h3><p>Spring (Mar-May) and autumn (Sep-Nov) offer comfortable weather. Summers are hot; winters are mild but occasionally foggy. Pandas are most active in morning feeding times.</p><h3 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">Getting around</h3><ul><li><strong>Metro:</strong> 12+ lines. Use the \"天府通\" app or transit card.</li><li><strong>Didi:</strong> Very convenient in Chengdu.</li><li><strong>Bicycle:</strong> Shared bikes (Hello, Meituan) available throughout.</li></ul><h3 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">Suggested itineraries</h3><p><strong>1 day:</strong> Panda Base (morning) -- Jinli Street (afternoon) -- Sichuan Opera in the evening.</p><p><strong>3 days:</strong> Day 1: Panda Base + Jinli Street; Day 2: Dujiangyan day trip; Day 3: People's Park + Wide and Narrow Alley + Sichuan cuisine.</p><h3 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-2\">Practical tips</h3><ul><li><strong>Sichuan food:</strong> Try mapo tofu, kung pao chicken, dan dan noodles, and Sichuan hotpot.</li><li><strong>Language:</strong> Mandarin is universal; translation apps help at local restaurants.</li><li><strong>Cash:</strong> Alipay/WeChat Pay dominant; carry cash for small vendors at Jinli Street.</li></ul>",
    "ogTitleChengdu": "Chengdu Travel Guide - Giant Pandas, Sichuan Cuisine & Cultural Heritage",
